The current proposal puts three separate concerns in one function: HTTP transport (`NextRequest`/`NextResponse`), application policy (approved-only invoicing and total calculation), and persistence (`prisma`). The smallest production design is to move the rule and action into one use case that owns plain input/output models and the ports it needs, then keep Next.js and Prisma as adapters.

A minimal shape:

```ts
// application/create-invoice.ts
export type CreateInvoiceCommand = {
  orderId: string;
};

export type CreateInvoiceResult = {
  invoiceId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export type OrderForInvoicing = {
  id: string;
  status: "APPROVED" | "PENDING" | "CANCELLED";
  lines: Array<{ amountCents: number }>;
};

export interface OrderForInvoicingReader {
  findById(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing | null>;
}

export interface InvoiceWriter {
  save(draft: { orderId: string; totalCents: number }): Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export class OrderNotApprovedError extends Error {}
export class OrderNotFoundError extends Error {}

export class CreateInvoice {
  constructor(
    private readonly orders: OrderForInvoicingReader,
    private readonly invoices: InvoiceWriter,
  ) {}

  async execute(command: CreateInvoiceCommand): Promise<CreateInvoiceResult> {
    const order = await this.orders.findById(command.orderId);
    if (!order) throw new OrderNotFoundError();
    if (order.status !== "APPROVED") throw new OrderNotApprovedError();

    const totalCents = order.lines.reduce((sum, line) => sum + line.amountCents, 0);
    const invoice = await this.invoices.save({ orderId: order.id, totalCents });

    return { invoiceId: invoice.id, totalCents };
  }
}
```

Ownership and translation points:

- Application layer owns `CreateInvoiceCommand`, `CreateInvoiceResult`, `OrderForInvoicingReader`, and `InvoiceWriter`.
- The use case owns the approval check and invoice-total calculation.
- Next.js route is only a controller/adapter: read `orderId` from the request, call `useCase.execute({ orderId })`, translate result/errors into HTTP status and JSON.
- Prisma adapters are only persistence translators: fetch Prisma rows, map them into `OrderForInvoicing`; persist invoice draft, map saved row into `{ id: string }`.
- Concrete wiring belongs at the outer edge, where the route or bootstrap code constructs `new CreateInvoice(prismaOrderReader, prismaInvoiceWriter)`.

That keeps the application action independent from both Next.js and Prisma without adding more architecture than this use case plus two ports. A minimal wiring sketch:

```ts
// adapters/http/create-invoice-route.ts
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const useCase = new CreateInvoice(
    new PrismaOrderForInvoicingReader(prisma),
    new PrismaInvoiceWriter(prisma),
  );

  try {
    const result = await useCase.execute({
      orderId: request.nextUrl.searchParams.get("orderId")!,
    });

    return NextResponse.json(result, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof OrderNotApprovedError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "not approved" }, { status: 409 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

If you want the smallest directory shape, organize it around the use case, not technology:

- `src/invoicing/create-invoice/application/create-invoice.ts`
- `src/invoicing/create-invoice/adapters/http/next-route.ts`
- `src/invoicing/create-invoice/adapters/persistence/prisma-order-reader.ts`
- `src/invoicing/create-invoice/adapters/persistence/prisma-invoice-writer.ts`

That is enough separation for production while keeping the rule, models, interfaces, translation, and wiring in the right ownership boundaries.
